<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
In soft sediment habitats outside the coral reef. Observed feeding on a pinnate form of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Agardh" authorityYear="1873" class="Bryopsidophyceae" family="Caulerpaceae" genus="Caulerpa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Caulerpa racemosa" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Caulerpa racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="ForsskÃ¥l">Forsskal</normalizedToken>
) J. Agardh, 1873 which is found chiefly in soft sediment habitats beyond the coral reef. A more lenticular/globular form of the algae can be abundant in some shallow, degraded reef habitats; however, specimens from Koh Tao not been observed associated with this variety. Depth 12-20 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
At present 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jensen" authorityYear="1997" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia tomentosa" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered widespread across the Indo-Pacific (but see remarks below) including Iran (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" author="Oladi, M" journalOrPublisher="Zoology in the Middle East" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="124 - 130" refId="B183" refString="Oladi, M, Nasrolahi, A, Ahmadzadeh, F, Alizadeh, O, Krug, P, 2018. Molecular confirmation of the occurrence of Elysia cf. tomentosa (Mollusca: Heterobranchia) in the Persian Gulf. Zoology in the Middle East 64: 124 - 130, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" title="Molecular confirmation of the occurrence of Elysia cf. tomentosa (Mollusca: Heterobranchia) in the Persian Gulf." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" volume="64" year="2018">Oladi et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
), Madagascar, Malaysia (
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
), Australia (
<bibRefCitation author="Jensen, KR" editor="Wells, FE" journalOrPublisher="Western Australian Museum, Perth" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="307 - 333" refId="B116" refString="Jensen, KR, 1997. Sacoglossa (Mollusca, Opisthobranchia) from the Houtman Abrolhos Islands and central Western Australia. In: Wells, FE, Ed., The Marine Flora and Fauna of the Houtman Abrolhos Islands, Western Australia. Western Australian Museum, Perth: 307 - 333" title="Sacoglossa (Mollusca, Opisthobranchia) from the Houtman Abrolhos Islands and central Western Australia." volumeTitle="The Marine Flora and Fauna of the Houtman Abrolhos Islands, Western Australia." year="1997">Jensen 1997</bibRefCitation>
), 
<normalizedToken originalValue="RÃ©union">Reunion</normalizedToken>
, India, Singapore, the Philippines, Indonesia, Japan, New Caledonia, and Hawaii (
<bibRefCitation author="Jensen, KR" journalOrPublisher="The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, Supplement" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="226 - 249" refId="B122" refString="Jensen, KR, 2015. Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) from northern coasts of Singapore. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, Supplement 31: 226 - 249" title="Sacoglossa (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) from northern coasts of Singapore." volume="31" year="2015">Jensen 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Likely introduced to the Mediterranean alongside the highly invasive 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.V.F.Lamouroux" authorityYear="1809" class="Bryopsidophyceae" family="Caulerpaceae" genus="Caulerpa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Caulerpa" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Caulerpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.12681/mms.87" author="Zenetos, A" journalOrPublisher="Mediterranean Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="381 - 493" refId="B297" refString="Zenetos, A, Gofas, S, Verlaque, M, Cinar, M, Garcia Raso, JE, Bianchi, CN, Morri, C, Azzurro, E, Bilecenoglu, M, Froglia, C, Siokou-Frangou, I, Violanti, D, Sfriso, A, San Martin, G, Giangrande, A, Katagan, T, Ballesteros, E, Ramos-Espla, AA, Mastrototaro, F, Ocana, O, Zingone, A, Gambi, MC, Streftaris, N, 2010. Alien species in the Mediterranean Sea by 2010. A contribution to the application of European Union's Marine Strategy Framework Directive (MSFD). Part I. Spatial distribution. Mediterranean Marine Science 11: 381 - 493, DOI: https://doi.org/10.12681/mms.87" title="Alien species in the Mediterranean Sea by 2010. A contribution to the application of European Union's Marine Strategy Framework Directive (MSFD). Part I. Spatial distribution." url="https://doi.org/10.12681/mms.87" volume="11" year="2010">Zenetos et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Here representing a first record for Thai waters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Recent molecular investigations have found that specimens recognised as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jensen" authorityYear="1997" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia tomentosa" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
likely correspond to a complex of at least six species (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" author="Krug, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular phylogenetics and evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1101 - 1119" refId="B141" refString="Krug, P, Vendetti, J, Rodriguez, A, Retana, J, Hirano, Y, Trowbridge, C, 2013. Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control. Molecular phylogenetics and evolution 69: 1101 - 1119, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" title="Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" volume="69" year="2013">Krug et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Discussions about the identity of specimens identifiable by black marginal lines along the parapodia and the similar species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O'Donoghue" baseAuthorityYear="1924" class="Gastropoda" family="Plakobranchidae" genus="Elysia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Elysia expansa" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="expansa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Elysia expansa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="OâDonoghue">O'Donoghue</normalizedToken>
, 1924) have yet to be resolved (
<bibRefCitation author="Rudman, WB" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22744" refId="B222" refString="Rudman, WB, 2009a. Elysia expansa? from India. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22744" title="Elysia expansa? from India. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22744" year="2009 a">Rudman 2009a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" author="Krug, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular phylogenetics and evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="1101 - 1119" refId="B141" refString="Krug, P, Vendetti, J, Rodriguez, A, Retana, J, Hirano, Y, Trowbridge, C, 2013. Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control. Molecular phylogenetics and evolution 69: 1101 - 1119, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" title="Integrative species delimitation in photosynthetic sea slugs reveals twenty candidate species in three nominal taxa studied for drug discovery, plastid symbiosis or biological control." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2013.07.009" volume="69" year="2013">Krug et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" author="Oladi, M" journalOrPublisher="Zoology in the Middle East" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="124 - 130" refId="B183" refString="Oladi, M, Nasrolahi, A, Ahmadzadeh, F, Alizadeh, O, Krug, P, 2018. Molecular confirmation of the occurrence of Elysia cf. tomentosa (Mollusca: Heterobranchia) in the Persian Gulf. Zoology in the Middle East 64: 124 - 130, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" title="Molecular confirmation of the occurrence of Elysia cf. tomentosa (Mollusca: Heterobranchia) in the Persian Gulf." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/09397140.2018.1444571" volume="64" year="2018">Oladi et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
recently documented a species in this complex from Iran that matches a sequence of 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" genus="E." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="E. tomentosa" order="Sacoglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tomentosa">E. cf. tomentosa</taxonomicName>
from the Andaman coast of Thailand, by Cornelius Swennen (GenBank accession number KC573755.1); however, no record of this species from the waters of Thailand has been found in the literature to date. Greater sampling efforts from more locations, with an assessment of internal characters, are needed to clarify this complex, including specimens from Koh Tao.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
